\begin_layout Subsection
The water footprint is too simplistic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The water footprint is expressed as a single number where everything adds
 up equally.
 So a liter of blue water is equated to a liter of gray water.
 Like the proponents of the water footprint, I am in favor of always explicitly
 naming the different colors of water.
 However, it's only human to want to lump everything together under one
 value, losing (important) nuance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do even the proponents of the water footprint do the same? Although
 they don't say why they suddenly leave the nuance behind, they justify
 the 1-to-1 addition by arguing that working with weights gives a subjective
 assessment of the colors to water.
 I find this an odd argument because implicitly they are using a subjective
 assessment where all forms of water use are considered equal.
\end_layout

