\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gray water is virtual water
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you saw in the definition of gray water, this value depends on legal
 standards.
 These standards change over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that, for example, the nuts above have a relatively high gray
 water footprint.
 But if the legislation changes, they suddenly have a different gray water
 footprint.
 The real impact on the environment hasn't changed however!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A green water footprint is not always bad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the water cycle, the great water cycle is well known.
 This is the cycle where water evaporates from the sea, passes over the
 land as clouds, precipitates and then flows back to the sea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the course of the Landwijzer training, we also learned about the
 small water cycle.
 This involves forests evaporating water which causes water to precipitate
 further inland.
 If you break this small water cycle, then there is an increased chance
 of desertification further from the sea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the restoration of the small water cycle that explains the successes
 in various places in the world where trees have been planted again, resulting
 in the restoration of rivers and streams.
 This made plots of land downstream more humid, which in turn made agriculture
 possible.
 Think for example of the successes filmed by John D.
 Liu or the work of Geoff Lawton.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here in Flanders, on the other hand, one is familiar with the usage of trees
 to make fields drier.
 Whether this is still desirable I will not say, but clearly the evapotranspirat
ion has the reverse effect as described above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both examples there is a high green water footprint.
 In one case, the water supply is replenished in an indirect way.
 In the other, the groundwater table is lowered.
 So it is clear that the consequences of a high green water footprint are
 not unambiguous.
 It depends a lot on the local situation: is there a surplus of precipitation
 or not.
\end_layout

